# Create dataset

The creation or acquisition of an appropriate dataset is one of the most critical for model performance. In this tutorial we will create our own dataset, using [Roboflow](https://roboflow.com/) (skip this part if you don't want your own dataset). Of course you can also use other annotation tools, here is some [help](https://docs.ultralytics.com/yolov5/tutorials/train_custom_data/#13-prepare-dataset-for-yolov5:~:text=download%20your%20dataset.-,Option%202%3A%20Create%20a%20Manual%20Dataset,-2.1%20Create%20dataset) on how to use them with YOLOv5.

## Collect images

To ensure good performance, it is necessary to collect at least 1500 images of each object to be learned. Since these images will be the basis for the model to learn what it needs to recognise, it is important to have a variety of images to use for training.

## Create Roboflow dataset

Once you have collected images, you will need to annotate the objects of interest to create a ground truth for your model to learn from. All you have to do is create a new workspace/project and upload your collected images there. If you have labeled images by default, Roboflow will automatically convert them to the correct format, otherwise you have to label them manually (for help with manual labelling click [here](https://docs.roboflow.com/annotate/use-roboflow-annotate)).

## Preparing the dataset for training

After the preparation of the training images is finished, it is required to generate the database. Here are some important settings:



*   Train/Test Split: Roboflow usually recommends a ratio of 80/10/10, in most cases it will be fine
*   Preprocessing: For our current use, let's choose the 640*640 setting. It is important to note that some [models](https://github.com/ultralytics/yolov5#pretrained-checkpoints) require different resolution as input, so it is important to set the correct value.
*   Augmentation: The collected images can be augmented. Certain changes can be made to the images (rotation, coloring, etc.), thus increasing the training dataset and, as expected, the model's performance, as it sees objects in more different positions. This step is implemented by default in the YOLOv5 teaching, so it is recommended to leave this empty when creating a roboflow dataset.
*   

We have the possibility to load our own or other people's dataset from [Roboflow Universe](https://universe.roboflow.com/). If you select a dataset, you can press the "Download Dataset" button to load it directly using code. Here we have to select "YOLO v5 PyToch" and "show download code" **It is important that you choose a dataset that contains a validation set, otherwise the YOLOv5 code will not be able to run.**

## Selecting the right model

The choice of the appropriate model depends largely on the task to be performed. Yolov5 has several types of pretrained models, which we only need to train further for our own task. The parameters of the different models can be found [here](https://github.com/ultralytics/yolov5#pretrained-checkpoints). For simplicity and speed, we will now use the smallest model: YOLOv5n.

## Training the selected model

There are a lot of [parameters](https://github.com/ultralytics/yolov5/blob/master/train.py#L513) that can be set for a YOLOv5 training, but for now we will only set some of the more important ones:

*   img: Size of images used for teaching
*   epochs: How many epochs to run the teaching. (In practice, it is better to use early stopping rather than directly specifying an expected epoch)
*   data: The path to the data.yaml file for our previously downloaded dataset. (It will be directly in the dataset folder)
*   weights: Our selected model.
